# Cloudflare Pages natively serves /page and /page.html with the same content,
# but this does NOT make them SEO-equivalent: both return 200, so Google can
# crawl and index both independently. Explicit 301s (below) are what actually
# consolidate ranking signals onto a single canonical URL.

# guides/index.astro builds to /guides.html (build.format: 'file' in astro.config.mjs
# outputs foo/index.astro as foo.html, not a foo/ directory). /guides/ was never a
# real path - the two rules that used to live here (/guides -> /guides/ and
# /guides.html -> /guides/) redirected working URLs to a 404. Fixed: redirect the
# non-existent /guides/ to the real page instead.
/guides/ /guides.html 301
/guides /guides.html 301

# Regular content/tool pages. astro.config.mjs uses build.format: 'file', so
# every page's real output is /page-name.html, and every canonical tag in
# Base.astro already points at the .html URL. Cloudflare Pages happens to also
# serve the same content at the extension-less path with a 200 (not a redirect),
# so Google was crawling and indexing BOTH /page-name and /page-name.html as
# separate URLs, splitting impressions/ranking signal between them (confirmed
# in GSC Pages.csv — e.g. /water-intake and /water-intake.html both indexed
# with separate impression counts). These 301s consolidate everything onto the
# single canonical .html URL, matching what canonical tags + internal nav links
# already say. Generated from the top-level src/pages/*.astro list, minus
# index/404 and the deprecated age/height pages already handled below.
